column3:
This morning at night, I woke from sleep and heard many voices of anguish,

My head was still spinning from the Spanish trip that had been so delightfully lavish;

I suddenly realized I was winning Amethi, ah, which is just a dirt track,

Such a saving grace from my dear sister, what a rearguard attack;

My joy was shortlived, as mummy threw a spanner in the works,

I had to join the evening press conference, such a burden of my perks;

During the day, I had to endure, the obligatory phone calls,

Drowning me in their sorrows, their defeatism which appals;

First on the line was that mighty minister who was the toast of Harvard,

Consoling me on my career graph, now irrevocably downward;

I am smart enough to pay the finance minister, back in his own coin,

Since his son couldn’t keep his father’s seat, there must be a pain in his groin;

A personal visit by his lawyer colleague, who was busy banning websites,

His campaign crashed like his Bentely car, in a tunnel without headlights;

Jindal Saheb, was gracious enough, but I asked him to pack a coal block,

Sail with the wind, take an insurance, slip it into Adani’s shoe rack;

Mani Shankar Aiyar sees my dad, even in his bathroom mirrors,

Now that he has lost, he can start correcting Hindu alumnus’ typographical errors;

Salmanbhai, he couldn’t taste blood, though his talk was all brawny,

He said, let me call the paki minister for a delightful biriyani;

Sushil saheb, our home minister, who was close to catching Dawood Ibrahim,

Before he was told ISI is not a quality seal, but a different acronym;

There are some traitors, who still won, and spoilt my sense of victory,

But saved me, my balloon and toffee from becoming election history;

The new bachelor had won his seat, that minister from united nation,

Already picking the next fruit, such great sense of occasion;

Oily Moily, scraped through, he can now relax in KG Basin villa,

Thanking his stars, now he needn’t sweep the floors of Antilla;

Kamal Nath always wins his seat, it may be a matter of routine,

But Modi has reset the password of his ATM machine;

Our allies and us shared the dharma of coalition politics,

The loss of UPA brings their house down, mortar and bricks;

Raja couldn’t fix the price, for his Nilgris constituency,

The voters knew how to value the 2G frequency;

Praful Patel has a lifetime now to fly his favourite airline,

Will he ever get back to cockpit, despite his receding hairline;

Laloo with his wife & daughter, cow & iron plough,

Could have been our saviour, but his fortune too hit a plateau;

But the wily fox Sharad Pawar, he knows how to bye pass a Tsunami,

He played his games around even my wily mommy;

He sent his daughter into the field, and saved himself from injury,

Why do women get all the genes, I wonder at nature’s mystery;

And then there are those who licked the honey without being elected,

But still cannot runaway without their reputation unaffected;

On the top is Diggy Singh, who taught me everything tactical,

But alas, all he can now do, is ink his prenuptial;

Then there was the Sardar with an attached toilet,

He, Ranga, MMS and Chidu, what a quadruplet;

It is now the appointed time for the press conference,

Didi tells me don’t tear the written statement, as another nonsense;

Ahmedbhai has typed it all in elementary Italian,

I have to read it out, in front of the media battalion;

I try to keep a sober face, the drill is about to begin,

But I finish my lines and slip into my stupid sheepish grin;

My momma takes the mike from me and keeps a brave face,

Superciliously greets the winner, totally lacking in grace;

I think it is mandatory to take atleast one audience query,

To comfort partymen who are in deep misery;

A gentle tug and a firm look, I shrink like a kitten,

Mama says simply get inside and read your Enid Blyton;

Victory and defeat are for the less blessed,

We are not wasting our life for these oppressed;

Congress may be in mourning, for five years they will languish,

Why don’t you see the silver lining, off to Venice we’ll vanish.

Thanks to a resounding victory over arch-rival Pakistan in the Asia Cupt T20 2016 match at Mirpur, Bangladesh, the Indian cricket team brought in some much-needed cheer and joy to the country, apart from a lot of worry to intellectual Ashis Nandy, who felt that the rise in nationalism levels was alarming. Reactions to the much-talked about match continued on social media, post the win. The UnReal Times correspondent Mark Zuckerpandian was on the job, as always, to bring you this compilation.

(Translations:

Bachchon ki kasam = promise on my kids;

Shastri ko hathaiye, aur Greg Chappell ko laiye = remove Shastri, bring in Greg Chappell;

Inzy khush hua = Inzy is happy;

Yeh kya bakwaas kar rahe hain yeh log? = What nonsense are these people doing?;

Njangalum undu mone, adipoli = We’re also in, son! Awesome!)
